	<td class="alt1">
	
		
			<!-- icon and title -->
			<div class="smallfont">
				
				<strong>My story (Not based on Civ III)</strong>
			</div>
			<hr size="1" style="color:#a62a2a" />
			<!-- / icon and title -->
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>This is my third attempt at writing a story.  Hopefully I'll finish it this time.  It is not based on a Civ III game.  I hope that is Okay with you guys <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="Smilie" class="inlineimg" />  Okay, here goes:<br />
<br />
China = green<br />
Korea = dark blue<br />
Japan = pink <br />
<br />
The early history of Asia is for a large part a mystery.  What little clues we have comes from oral traditions, which are not, however, backed by hard tangible evidence.  We can only briefly describe what we think happened, with the caveat that very much is still unknown and that what we do know is based on sources that are at best suspicious in its authenticity.  <br />
<br />
Myths tell us of a dragon who would emerge from the Yellow River once every two or three years and eat the people who live along the river.  In the process, families were destroyed and many people were killed.  Various attempts had been made by the people who lived along the Yellow River to slay the dragon; but they all failed ultimately.  The people lived in fears, yet they had no choice of moving outside the Yellow River basin for beyond lied the vast unknown as well as barren land that was unsuitable to the agricultural lifestyle that these people had developed.  Several generations went by and a man by the name of Yu was born.  He, according to legend, killed the dragon and was, as a result of his accomplishment, made the king.  <br />
<br />
Archaeologists and mythologists interpreted the dragon simply as flood that constantly threatened the livelihood of the people who lived along the Yellow River.  As for Yu, it wasn’t so much that he killed the dragon as that he took effective measures that successfully controlled the flood.  Such measures included the building of dams, irrigations, and other flood controlling infrastructures.  <br />
<br />
However, to build these infrastructures was formidable tasks given the state of technology in the dawn of civilization.  In order to mobilize the labor force and resources for such a project, some kind of central authority must have already been in place.  Writing systems as well as arithmetic must have also developed during this time as part of the effort to coordinate and organize resources and labor.  In fact, historians believed that Chinese civilization was one that emerged as a response to the flood.  Put another way, it was the challenge presented by the Yellow River’s deluge that pushed the early Chinese ancestors to eventually conquer the nature, and, through it, laid the foundation of an empire.  <br />
<br />
Fast forwarding several centuries, and we see a vastly different picture along the Yellow River.  By 3500 BC, cities emerged.  Trading thrived, and the use of currency was introduced to facilitate commerce.  A government based on monarchy was clearly in place.  It is from this time and onward that we have accurate and reliable written source of information regarding what happened in this region.<br />
<br />
In the summer of 3542 BC, Emperor Yao sat at his palace contemplating over what to do with the six primitive tribes that located their homes to the West of the then Shang dynasty China.  The six primitive tribes were ferocious warriors who frequently raided the western most frontier of the Shang kingdom.  Emperor Yao’s predecessors had dealt traditionally dealt with such a threat by paying tributes to each tribe.  However, unfortunately for Emperor Yao, such option was not viable in this particular year.  News of possible bad harvest meant small tax revenues.  This would have been fine for Emperor Yao if he did not have to pay tributes to the six western tribes; but he had to.  <br />
<br />
Emperor Yao, a competent and benevolent king whose rule began when he was fifteen, inherited a kingdom that was build on a healthy foundation of political stability, much to his father’s credit.  In the thirteen years since he had taken over, Emperor Yao build on this foundation, promoted trading, and embarked on major construction projects to enhance intercity commerce.  As a result, his kingdom prospered.  Unintentionally, this prosperity only invited increasing raids from those barbarians.  <br />
<br />
Among the six barbarian tribes, the two most powerful ones were the Nujen, and Xiongnu.  They occupied a region to the west of Shang China that was most fertile to farming.  It was this that gave these two tribes the economic strength to dominate all four others, namely the Yamato, Choson, Xixia, and Chidan.  <br />
<br />
Emperor Yao sat in his palace the entire afternoon until dinner time.  And by the time that servants had brought dinner to him, he had an idea.  <br />
<br />
The next day, Emperor Yao sent for his most trusted advisor, Yong Ming, to come for a secret consultation.  Later, in the same day, Yong Ming embarked on a journey westward for Xiongnu’s territory.  Going with him were six carts of silk scrolls, ten carts of wines, fifteen carts of rice, a hundred cows and cattle, and thirty prisoners who were on death rolls.  <br />
<br />
Yong Ming arrived at Xiongnu’s territory three days later and met with the chief of the Xiongnu tribe, Yuei Dei Guang.  And the following conversation took place.  <br />
<br />
Yong:  On behalf of my emperor, I bring these presents to you, as well as a request for help.  As you know, Shang dynasty has for the last two hundred years been paying tributes annually to your majesty and the Nuden.  Yet, I fear that this will not be possible for this year, because of an impending drought that will spell bad harvest.  But more importantly, the house of Shang is in trouble.  Emperor Yao is greatly ill, and his four children are watching anxiously for his death in order to inherit the throne.  Although by tradition, the oldest son is suppose to inherit the throne, all other three have commanded the loyalty of a substantial portion of the Shang army.  Emperor Yao fears that his death will translate into civil war that would pit his four sons against each other.  It is for this reason that Emperor Yao has sent for me to see you.  <br />
<br />
Yuei:  I see.  And how may I be of an assistance?  <br />
<br />
Yong:  Emperor Yao wants his first son, Xia Jie, to inherit the throne for he is the undoubtedly the right choice. He is benevolent and intelligent.  Ever since the young age of five, he was brought to every single meeting between his father and the imperial advisors to be apprise of the events in the country.  He has studied history and is well versed in the political administration.  On numerous occasions, he was given important tasks which he executed with great competence.   It is therefore he who must be the next emperor.  <br />
But there is a problem.  He has no command of any army like his three other younger brothers.  This is because Xia Jie was so involved in aiding his father with the administration of the country that he had little time to devote to forming his own factions.  This would put him in a very dangerous situation once Emperor Yao dies.  It is therefore our humble wish that you intervene in this matter by sending your army to Shang and declare support for Xia Jie once Emperor Yao dies.  Everyone under the heaven knows that Xiongnu’s army is the most powerful.  Your army’s presence in Shang alone will be a sufficient deterrent which would prevent Xia Jei’s three brothers from act of treachery.  <br />
<br />
Yuei:  I am honored to be held in such high esteem.  Let me confer with my advisors and I shall give you a reply tomorrow.  <br />
<br />
That night, Yuei Dei Guang met with his two brothers, Yuei Dei Liang, and Yuei Dei Chong to discuss the matter brought up by Yong Ming.  <br />
<br />
Liang:  I have asked the slaves that Yong had brought along with him.  They have all confirmed that Emperor Yao is indeed dying.  This is a god send opportunity for us to conquer Shang.  In the past, when our armies invaded Shang, we were only successful at raiding, but were never able to conquer the kingdom because of its strong fortification and army.  Now, we are given an opportunity to march our army into Shang without any resistance, we must agree to Yong’s request.  Once our army is inside the Shang territory, we will easily be able to conquer the kingdom.  <br />
<br />
Chong:  Something is telling me that this is a trick.  Emperor Yao is not a stupid man.  He knew better than to let our army go inside of his kingdom.  <br />
<br />
Guang:  I agree with Chong.  Yet, I also have to admit that this is a rare opportunity.  I do not wish to let it go so easily.  This is my plan.  One of you will go back to Shang tomorrow with Yong.  You will bring the army that you command with you.  There in Shang, you will examine and verify the authenticity of all that was said by Yong today.  Your being inside Shang with your army can also be an advantage to us when we initiate our invasion of Shang.  In another word, you will collect information about Shang’s military and help clear the way for our invasion.  Which one of you is willing to go?<br />
<br />
Chong volunteered, and all was settled.  The next day, Guang went back to Shang with Yong Ming according to the plan.  When Emperor Yao met Chong, he rejoiced at Xiongnu’s willingness to help and offered to pay tributes to Xiongnu has Shang had always done for the past two hundred years regardless of the drought.  This was done with the understanding that once the tributes were paid to Xiongnu, nothing would be left to pay to Nujen.  Chong was much pleased by this.  He was also convinced that Emperor Yao was dying soon, judging by the feebleness that was so clearly evident in Emperor Yao’s voice, posture, and actions.  Yet, little did Chong and his two brothers back in Xiongnu territory know that all this was a trap.<br />
<br />
Meanwhile in Nujen, Chief Bai Mu Da was clearly upset.  He was upset because he had just received news that Shang will not be bringing tributes to him this year.  Moreover, Shang chose to instead bring tributes to only Xiongnu.  But what angered him the most was the fact that Emperor Yao of Shang asked Xiongnu, but not Nujen, for help in what was going to be a political upheaval in the Shang kingdom.  All these seriously threatened Nujen’s status as the dominant tribe among the six.  In addition, Chief Bai knew that Xiongnu would use this opportunity to gain control of Shang, effectively making Xiongnu even more powerful than Nujen.  This would tip the balance of power in Xiongnu’s favor, and eventually destroy Nujen’s future.  The thought of this possibility scared Chief Bai, and he decided to act fast. <br />
<br />
In the late summer of 3542 BC, things seemed to be settled.  Emperor Yao had completely handed over the task of national administration to his first son Xia Jie, although Emperor Yao was still the official ruler in name.  While, Xiongnu was making preparation for invasion of Shang as soon as Emperor Yao dies. <br />
<br />
In mid September, when fall approached, news reached to Xiongnu that Emperor Yao had passed away, and that Shang is on the verge of political turmoil as Xia Jie’s three brothers fought for control of the throne.  Upon hearing this, Yuei Dei Guang readied his army, and marched for Shang, leaving Yuei Dei Liang to guard the Xiongu territory.  <br />
<br />
Half way to Shang, however, Yuei Dei Guang’s army was ambushed the Nujen’s army.  Chief Bai of Nujen had been keeping up with development in Shang, and knew of the invasion that Yuei was undertaking.  In order to prevent Yuei from successfully conquering Shang, Chief Bai launched his own surprise invasion on Xiongnu.  The army Chief Bai led attacked Yuei Dei Guang’s army, while Chief Bai’s brother attacked Xiongnu territory directly herself.  <br />
<br />
Although Xiongnu and Nujen were equal in military strength, Xiongnu’s army was divided into three.  One third of it was already in Shang.  The other third was back in Xiongnu territory.  The remaining third was the one led by Yuei Dei Guang himself.  In contrast, Nujen’s army was split into only two, one attacking Yuei Dei Guang, while the other attacked Xiongnu homeland.  This gave Nujen a numerical advantage, which was amplified because Nujen ambushed Yuei’s army.  Nujen quickly destroyed Yuei Dei Guang’s and Yuei Dei Liang’s army, leaving Yuei Dei Chong’s army back in Shang completely helpless to do anything.  <br />
<br />
When news of Nujen’s successful invasion of Xiongnu reached Shang, Chong asked that Shang help Xiongnu.  In particular, Chong threatened Xia Jie to withdraw his army from Shang altogether leaving Xia Jie to perish in the struggle against his brother for Shang’s throne.  However, Chong soon realized that he had felt completely into a trap when Emperor Yao, who was supposed to have passed away, emerged and sat down on the imperial throne.  The struggle among Emperor Yao’s four sons was all along just a lie as well as his own death.  This meant that the four sons’ army would not disunite to fight each other, but would instead band together to destroy Chong’s army, which did happen.  <br />
<br />
At the same time, Nujen’s successful conquest of Xiongnu did not go without loss.  Xiongnu was defeated, but they put up a brave fight, causing Nujen substantial losses.  Nujen tried to compensate for this loss by ordering the four other smaller tribes, the Choson, Yamato, Xixia, and Chidan, to pay tributes.  This aroused much discontent among the four smaller tribes.  Emperor Yao, loosing no time, formed secret alliance with the four smaller tribes.  In October of 3542 BC, a combined army of Choson, Yamato, Xixia, Chidan, and Shang marched into Nujen, who was still recovering from the war with Xiongnu.  Too weak to fight, Nujen quickly felt.  <br />
<br />
The former Xiongnu and Nujen territories were partitioned among the four tribes.  However, the four tribes quickly became discontent with the partitioning, and fought amongst themselves.  Emperor Yao of Shang took advantage of this and grabbed some more territories.  Meanwhile during the struggle among the four tribes, Xixia, and Chidan followed the fate of Xiongnu and Nujen, leaving Yamato and Choson to inherit the vast tract of land west of Shang kingdom.<br />
<br />
By 3541 BC, a new political order of Far East Asia had emerged.  Shang dynasty China had successfully emerged to become the undisputed master, no longer paying tributes to any foreign powers.  Yamato and Choson would increasingly abandon their barbaric and nomadic way of life and follow the way of Shang dynasty China.  A century of peace would follow in which Yamato and Choson would increasingly borrow from China, adopting her culture, institutions and technologies.  The kingdom of Yamato would later become Japan, and Choson become Korea.  These two would later become strong and challenge the might of Shang dynasty China.  The history of East Asia from this point on will be the story of struggle between these three nations for control of continental unification.  But for now, we turn westward to another part of the world.  There, something equally exciting was happening.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
