<tr valign="top">
	<td class="alt2" width="175">
			
			<div id="postmenu_2404322">
				
				<a class="bigusername" href="member.php?s=30d7bc45e6ae4cac0c8528356785e547&amp;u=1420">ShadowWarrior</a>
				<script type="text/javascript"> vbmenu_register("postmenu_2404322", true); </script>
				
			</div>
			
			<div class="smallfont">Warlord</div>
			
		
			
			
			<div class="smallfont">
				&nbsp;<br />
				<div>Join Date: Jun 2001</div>
				
				
				<div>
					Posts: 117
				</div>
				
				<div>   </div>
			</div>					
		
	</td>
	<td class="alt1">
	
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>There is a legend among the Greeks that in a time very long ago, when words were still not invented, a king ruled his Grecian subjects with an unprecedented cruelty in a city called Thyparathus.  We no longer know of this king’s name, only that the people referred to him as the “devil’s king”, which is how we will also refer to him from now on.  <br />
<br />
Legend has it that the devil’s king’s oppressive rule became so burdensome that two major migrations out of Thyparathus led to establishment of two major colonies, one to Thyparathus’ distant north, the other to her distant south.  Geographical barriers and pure distance alone gave these two cities the good fortune of protection from the devil’s king.  <br />
<br />
But in those two new cities were emerged their own devil’s kings, whose equally oppressive rule would propel their own waves of migration that would lead to establishment of yet new cities.  And in those new cities, devil’s kings emerged again only to lead to the same process, which would repeat over and over again until Greece is what she is today; she’s a completely divided nation comprise of many small city states, each with a king.  <br />
<br />
For many generations, the subject of most of the city states have lived in oppressive rule, and their liberation must wait until when another new city was founded, to which they could migrate, with the understanding that the kind of freedom from tyranny found in that new city could only last for several decades, if they are lucky enough.  Such is the sad political history of Greece up until the founding of Athens.  <br />
<br />
Athen was founded in 3577 BC, by a name called Plygorethesis.  He was a scholar at Sparta, the then undisputed master of all Greece.  Sparta, as Plygorethesis rightly observed, built her strength on constant warfare.  Her superior military, due to life long trainings that were required of any male children whenever they turned five, led her to numerous victory, until her name alone was enough to scare the rival into voluntary submission before a fight.  So strong and persistent was Sparta’s reputation as great warriors that when Spartan military has declined in her actually quality, many still submitted to Sparta as vessels.  <br />
<br />
Inside of Sparta, the glory of Spartan’s military victory gave way to an onerously dark world where civilians lived a life that reduced them to sub-human status.  Spartan culture was based on war, and so military class dominated the top of the social ladder.  Yet, the military class abused their social status.  They imposed heavy taxations on the Spartan subjects.  Laws were passed by the Spartan government, controlled by Spartan military class, that daughters were subject to “performing her sexual duties” to any man of military whenever he wishes for it to be done.  Farmers’ livelihood was constantly threatened as Spartan military frequently held huge hunting and other sport events, many of which involved many chariots making their way across farm fields, damaging the crops, and leading to reduced harvest.  Heavy taxation made things worse as farmers had only very little to live on after they paid the taxes.  Mass starvation after the taxation season was an annual occurrence, and corpse would litter the Spartan streets.  <br />
<br />
Plygorethesis founded Athen with an ideal.  He wanted to change Greece for Greece nation has been ruled by too many devil’s kings.  Being a philosopher, he had reasoned out a form of government that he thought was the best for the people.  It was called democracy.<br />
<br />
Democracy is a political system based on giving voice and power to the people, who would together decide on resolution of issues through a voting mechanism.  Other political institutions were also created that conformed to Plygorethesis’ ideal of democracy, such as respect for natural right of individual, and prevention of tyranny.  Plygorethesis’ Athen soon became the envy of all Grecian city-states.  Athen attracted an incredibly many waves of migrations.  Many of those who migrated to Athen were men of talents, who saw in Athen opportunities for them to unleash their own potential and to live a life away from tyranny.  And so very quickly, in less than a decade, Athen had grown into a major metropolis of a million and half.  <br />
<br />
Athen’s rapid and remarkable rise was an anomaly in Grecian history.  In all of her history, no one city-state had attracted such a huge number of migrants in so short a time.  And never before had a city-state had a happier atmosphere.  Wealth was so great in Athen that a typical Athenian was able to enjoy the kind of comfort that was the exclusive domain of aristocrats in other city-states.  Science, arts, literatures flourished because many of the migrants who moved here were themselves talented and learned men.  <br />
<br />
Yet, it was this rapid rise of Athen that also made her dangerous to many of her rival city-states.  In particular, Sparta, who had enjoyed the status as the absolute master of all Greeks for almost a century and half now, was determined to destroy Athen, and plunder her wealth.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
