	<td class="alt1">
	
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>In the early spring of 3559 BC, Athenian king, Marcus, met with Atticus diplomat, who brought news of the Atticusian king’s wish to marry his daughter to King Marcus.  The proposal was at best suspicious and at worst a trick, although it was not immediately known to King Marcus the exact nature of such a trick.  It was nevertheless a ploy because Atticus had traditionally paid tributes to Sparta.  A marriage proposal of this kind would, when executed, effectively make Atticus and Athen ally.  This shift in allegiance is unfathomable in absence of any compelling reason of which King Marcus knows none.  <br />
<br />
However, the only way to find out what Atticusian’s designs is, King Marcus must pretend to fall for the trap, which he did.  King Marcus married the Atticusian princess, Jocasta, and for the next several month of their marriage put up a show of good will and love for his newly wedded wife, a task that was not formidable given his wife’s heavenly beauty. <br />
<br />
On a late summer night, after having entertained the Atticusian diplomat who accompanied Princess Jocasta to her wedding ceremony, King Marcus pretended to be drunk.  Princess Jocasta had to help King Marcus to his bed.  Convinced that King Marcus was deep asleep, Princess Jocasta went to the Atticusian diplomat’s guest room, not knowing that she was being followed.  <br />
<br />
In the room, Princess Jocasta described what she has seen of Athen in the several month she has been here.  Of particular importance is Athen’s military status, major fortifications, weaponry, and other vital military information all of which Princess Jocasta revealed in great details.  Finished with the conversion, Princess Jocasta went back to her chamber to rest with her husband.  <br />
<br />
While resting in her chamber next to her husband, she could not sleep.  She was thinking what else she should do to secure more information about Athen’s military in order to clear way for an impending invasion by the joint army from Sparta and Atticus.  Suddenly, her husband, still quite drunk, muttered something.  Unable to understand the mumbling, Princess Jocasta did manage to make out two words that were of interest to her.  The two words were “invade” and “Atticus”.  <br />
<br />
Shocked, Princess Jocasta wished for her husband to say more.  Her wish was granted as her husband began to speak in great detail of his plan to invade Atticus.  Princess Jocasta learned that Marcus had planned all along to invade Atticus when their marriage began.  Specifically, Marcus had planned to concentrate the entire Athenian military on first striking a small farming town a few miles to the north of the Atticusian capital.  This farming town was strategic to Atticusian’s food supply.  Deprived of it, Atticusian military would completely collapse.  Princess Jocasta also learned of two other city-states near both Sparta and Atticus who had signed secret alliance with Athen.  When the Athenian invasion begins, these two city-states would also enter the war on the side of Athen.  Equipped with these information, Princess Jocasta rushed quietly to the diplomat’s room again to communicate her newly learned knowledge.  The next day, the diplomat departed for Atticus.  <br />
<br />
In the early fall of 3559 BC, the Athenian army marched for Atticus.  The Atticusian army was stationed at the very farming town that supplied the city-state’s bulk of food supply.  There, the Atticusian army readied themselves.  Formations were arranged, military installations were built, and ambush was prepared.  The Atticusians were waiting there, hoping to surprise the Athenian army.<br />
<br />
At the same time, Spartan army were divided into two.  One set out South, the other to the north.  Both went to conquer and punish the very city-states with whom a secret alliance has been signed with Athen.  <br />
<br />
Upon almost reaching the farming town, the Athenian army suddenly changed course, quickly marched for Atticusian capital.  Upon reaching the capital, Athenian army took it down with relatively ease because the bulk of the Atticusian army was stationed several miles away in the farming town.  The sudden change of event took the Atticusian army by surprise.  <br />
<br />
However, the Athenian army left the Atticusian capital as quickly as they have conquered it.  The Athenian army was clearly marching for Sparta, whose army was still fighting the two other city-states that allied with Athen.  Seeing this, the Atticusian army quickly re-deployed their entire army back to the Atticusian capital.  As soon as the Atticusian army reached their capital to liberate it, the Athenian army suddenly split into two.  One continued to head toward Sparta, while the other changed course and raced for the Atticusian farming town.  <br />
<br />
Upon reaching the Atticusian farming town, which was now completely undefended, the Athenian army destroyed the town, and all its farm field, and burned all the food supply.  Meanwhile the Athenian army that marched for Sparta quickly brought down the Spartan capital city for Spartan army was engaged in wars abroad.  The Spartan king was captured, made prisoner of war, and was sent back to Athen.<br />
<br />
The first war that Athen carried out since its founding ended in a costless victory for Athen.  Atticus suffered a famine in that same year due to lack of food supply, which was destroyed by the Athenian army.  And as for the Spartan, their capital city was ransacked.  When news of this reached the Spartan army fighting abroad, the entire army was so demoralized that they were quickly defeated.  Later, it was learned that Athen had never made any alliance with any city-states in Spartan’s sphere of influence.  The sly and cunning Athenian king, Marcus, made up everything he said that night while pretending to be drunk.  <br />
<br />
With Spartan’s sudden loss of power, the entire region within Spartan’s sphere of influence turned into chaos.  City-states began to fight with one another for control of mastery, while Athen watched as these city-states weaken themselves through this infighting.  The next year, King Marcus proposed the formation of an alliance between Athen and nine other nearby city-states under Marcus’ leadership.  And as things settled down in the former Spartan sphere of influence and war subsided five years after the formation of the Athenian led alliance, members of the former Spartan vessel system watched with alarm at the growing might of Athen, and decided to come together to form an alliance of their own to counter Athen. <br />
<br />
By 3555 BC, Greek’s new political landscape is in place.  Although city-states system was still in place, Athen would increasingly centralize power.  To the north of the future Athenian empire lied a Confederation which comprise all the territories that were formerly within Sparta’s sphere of influence.  For the next one decade, the two would face each other, engaged in a cold war that won’t turn hot in another sixty years.  At the same time, to the even more distant north, the growing empire of Persia sat quietly watching.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
