		<div>Persian expansion:<br />
<br />
By 3577 BC, Persia had mastered the kingdoms and tribes that sat in the Middle East.  Three hundred years ago, King Xerxes I united all Persian tribes under his rule, and created the first united Persian kingdom.  Ever since, his successors had built on his legacy and expanded Persia, swallowing various other tribes and kingdoms until the Egyptian-Persian war of 3592 BC, in which an Egyptian victory checked further Persian expansion down into Europe.  <br />
<br />
However, this defeat proved to be only a temporary set back for the Persians, who immediately changed plans, and attacked India.  At the time of the invasion, India was being torn apart by internal civil war as princes fought their siblings for control of the India’s Gulpta empire.  (I made the name because I am not well versed in Indian history.  For that matter, I am not well versed in any countries’ history except that of China’s.  I hope the name isn’t offensive to anyone.  If it is, I apologize in advance.)  As a result, Persia easily conquered a divided India.  Using the resources obtained from India, Persian quickly rebuild her wealth and the army lost during the war against Egypt, and by 3577 BC crushed the Egyptian resistance, destroying the Egyptian empire forever after she had stood for one thousand years.  <br />
<br />
Below, we trace the story of Persian expansion under Xerxes VIII’s, and, more specifically, his successful annexation of India and Egypt.</div>
