	<td class="alt1">
	
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>The Egyptian Persian War:<br />
<br />
King Xerxes VIII of Persia stood on top of the Goshan mountain (a random name I made up) overlook the long stretch of pasture that domesticated his army’s horses.  Beyond the pasture is the Serian Lake (another name I made up) that divides Persia and Egypt.   Xerxes watched and thought.  <br />
<br />
By the time of King Xerxes’ rule, the Egyptian empire had stood for a thousand year.  Although the rise of Persia three centuries ago had overshadowed the once mighty Egyptian empire, Persia still must conquer Egypt and India in order to achieve the status as the undisputed master of all Middle East.   <br />
<br />
The problem isn’t so much that a Persian invasion of Egypt would be difficult for it was not.  Persian army was the most powerful in Middle East in terms of size and quality.  What made Xerxes hesitated from carrying out an outright attack on Egypt was the consideration that it might perhaps be even better to first bring down India’s Gulpta empire, which was on the verge of civil war as the Indian princes fought their sibling for control of the empire’s throne.   However, an attack on India would no doubt alert the Egyptians into military preparation.  Persian army may be powerful, but Egyptian army was not weak either.  Xerxes’ confidence on being able to conquer Egypt rested on the element of surprise, one which would be lost if Persia invades India, thereby galvanizing Egyptians into actions.   <br />
<br />
Xerxes walked along a dirt path leading to a nearby town, where he and his advisors had been dwelling for the last few days.  By the time Xerxes had reached the town, he had made up his mind.  Five days later, the first regiment of Persian army would arrive to meet with Xerxes.   Three days after that, the rest of the Persian army stationed throughout the empire would also join force.  The first Persian-Egyptian war would soon begin.  <br />
<br />
--------------------------<br />
<br />
Queen Cleopatra was deep asleep when she was awakened forcefully by her servant.  Annoyed, Cleopatra asked indignantly the reason that she was awakened.  Responding to Cleopatra's inquiry, her servant said wth great panic that news had several hours ago reached Thebes, the Egyptian capital, that a huge Persian army of no less than sixty thousand had crossed the Serian Lake just a day ago, and will march to Thebes in four days.   <br />
<br />
As if not grasping the event that is now happening which her servant had communicated to her, Cleopatra simply stared, her jaw slightly dropping open.  But Cleopatra quickly recollected her thought, and dispatched the servant to call on all her imperial advisors to the palace for meeting.   <br />
<br />
The meeting however was not fruitful, it being better characterized by shouting matches in which advisors blamed each other for the disaster that has befallen.  The truth is the advisors themselves did not know what to do because an invasion was something that they, nor anyone in Egypt for that matter, had ever experienced.   Although the Egyptian hegemony had ended three hundred years ago with the rise of Persia, Egypt had up until now been spared from the Persian invasion because the Persians was preoccupied on elsewhere.  And so for three hundred years, Egypt had enjoyed peace.   Yet this peace made the quality of Egyptian military weak, a negative that admittedly was balanced out by the positve of the wealth and rich that the peace brought about.  However, no greater wealth and riches could save Egypt from the giagantic Persian army now.   <br />
<br />
Cleopatra dismissed her imperial advisors, who were giving her a headache rather than a head relief.  She sat down on a chair.  Her mind was blank.  She tried to think of something to do to save Egypt from the catastrophe, yet nothing came to her mind.   <br />
<br />
At this momment, Asire walked in.  He was also in the meeting that ended only minutes ago.  Cleopatra looked at him, and asked him of the reason for his return.  <br />
<br />
&quot;How much do you wish to save Egypt?&quot;, Asire asked.  <br />
&quot;If my death must be the price for Egypt's freedom from Persia, then so be it&quot;<br />
&quot;Death shall not be, for I have a plan that would obviate such need&quot;<br />
&quot;What do you have in mind?&quot;  Cleopatra asked, her eyes betraying her skepticism as she examined the young and relatively inexperienced advisor standing before her.  <br />
<br />
After Asire had communicated to Cleopatra of his idea, Cleopatra's skepticism turned to careful optimism.  <br />
<br />
&quot;It is a good plan, but it is nevertheless a risky one, which would destroy my kingdom if not executed perfectly&quot;<br />
&quot;That you would not need to worry, if you will let me be in charge&quot;<br />
&quot;And I will, and you shall be handsomely rewarded if you save Egypt.  Realize however that if you fail, your death shall not be because of my punishment, but because of that of the Persian's&quot;<br />
<br />
Asire nodded, the look of confidence on his face retreated a little, signalizing his realization at the severity of the great crisis that would ensue if he should make any mistake.</div>
