	<td class="alt1">
	
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>Cleopatra made it known to everyone the next day that she was heading east towards Ramesis, a city on the eastern most tip of Egypt.  Going along with her were the core of Egypt's army.  There at Ramesis, Cleopatra would reorganize and build a provisional capital, and amass the strength to liberate Egypt from the Persian tyranny.   Cleopatra's speech was delivered with such power that it aroused the emotion of all her audience.  As she leaves, her subject shouted &quot;long live Queen Cleopatra&quot;, and wished her fast return.  <br />
<br />
News of her speech and her leaving quickly spread throughout Egypt, and reached Xerxes.  He sat inside his tent, and thought.  Then he made up his mind.  <br />
<br />
&quot;Men!&quot;, Xerxes said to his generals, &quot;we are heading straight for Ramesis now!&quot;  <br />
<br />
His generals listened in confusion, and Lydus asked &quot;What of the cities that sit in between here and Ramesis?  The Egyptian army is in disarray.  We should conquer and consolidate our rule in these cities before we head for Ramesis while it is still easy to do.&quot;<br />
<br />
&quot;Your right about Egyptian army being in disarray.  In fact, as we speak now, all of Egypt is in disarray.  And that disarray will only get worse if we can capture Cleopatra and destroy the army that is now heading toward Ramesis with her.  Do you not see what Cleopatra is doing?   With her speech and her leaving for Ramesis, she has ignited a hope for all Egyptians that doom has not come.  As long as that hope exists, we will face resistance everywhere we go.  But as soon as we capture Cleopatra and destroy her army, Egyptian will loose the hope.   They will offer no resistance, and our task at conquering each city will be made all the more simpler.&quot;<br />
<br />
Xerxes' generals listened and nodded and praised Xerxes' for his cunning military strategy.  They left immediately for Ramesis.  In fact, Xerxes was so desperate to get to Ramesis that his entire army traveled long distances daily, loosing rest and sleep.   Upon reaching Ramesis, Xerxes' army was completely exhausted.</div>
