	<td class="alt1">
	
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>Yet to everyone's surprise, Xerxes saw no Egyptian army nor Cleopatra at Ramesis.  All they saw was an abandoned city.  On the door of the gate that led to the interior of the city was carved Persian writing, which said &quot;you have fallen for our trap&quot;.   <br />
<br />
Xerxes' mouth dropped open as he saw the writing.  At the same time, a Persian scout, completely injured exhausted, had rushed to Ramesis to deliver to Xerxes of what had happened.<br />
<br />
It turned out that Cleopatra never left Thebes.  She lied in order get Xerxes and his entire army to rush to Ramesis as soon as possible.  This would spare all the Egyptian city from Persian attack.  Meanwhile, as Xerxes marched towards Ramesis, the lightly guarded Persian warships that still docked along the Serian Lake was attacked by the Egyptian army, which now had complete control over the Persian ships.   <br />
<br />
Xerxes listened in shock as he realized what had happened.  If the Egyptians controlled the Persian ships, how will they ever be able to cross the Serian lake to get home?  The thought of this question scared Xerxes, and he quickly ordered the entire army to march westward back to Serian lake.   There, Xerxes' decided, they would fight to death if that is what must be done to get back control of the ship.  <br />
<br />
Yet, Xerxes and his army's return trip to Serian Lake was interrupted by numerous ambush planned earlier by Asire.  Worse yet, much of these ambush happened at night while the Persian army slept.  By the time the Persian reached the Serian lake, they were exhausted and completely demoralized.   <br />
<br />
The Persian army's will to fight was weakened further when they saw that the Egyptian had destroyed half of the Persian warships.  The remaining Persian warships were curiously unguraded by any Egyptian troops.  The Persian army camped along the bank that docked those Persian warships that were thought to have been occupied.   They dared not enter those ships for they fear traps.  <br />
<br />
The next morning, when scouts were sent aboard the ship, it was known that these ships were indeed empty, and in good health.  Grateful, Xerxes made preparation to embark, knowing that only half of his army could reach home, while the remaining half would have to stay behind.   <br />
<br />
At this very moment as the embark began, war drums and sound of horse chariots and screams emanated from all four directions.  The Egyptian army appeared suddenly out of nowhere surrounding the Persian army.  Yet, the Egyptians made only a half hearted effort at attacking the Persian army.   As for the Persian army, they had not the heart to fight for they were only concerned with getting back onto those ships, which they know would only carry half of the entire army back to Persia.  In the chaos that followed, Persian army was decimated slowly and slowly.   By the time the Persian warships left, only one third of the Persian army survived.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
