		<!-- message -->
		<div>Asire stood next to Cleopatra, his face shoned with pride.  His plan worked splendidly.  In fact, he was surprised by how successfully things went.  He created the illusion that Cleopatra's moving to Ramesis was a ray of hope that would inspire Egyptians to resistance against the Persians.   And the knowledge of this would lead Xerxes' to rush straight to Ramesis in an attempt to crush that ray of hope.  Yet, this was a trap, which gave the Egyptian an opportunity to take control of the Persian ships docked along the Serian lake.  And by destroying only half of the Persian ships, the Persian army would be too concerned with getting back onto those ships instead of fighting the Egyptians.   This psychological warfare was executed beautifully, and lead to the loss of two third of the Persian army.  What amazed Asire was not that his plan worked, for he knew that it would.  It was the amount of damage that was done to Persian army that amazed him.   <br />
<br />
Asire was made the commander of all Egyptian army, a title that he unfortunately could not keep for long because he soon died of a disease.  All of Egypt mourned for his death, yet they also quickly forgot about Asire.  Cleopatra, for her own part, was relieved that Asire had left the world for she feared his intelligence would lead him to betray her one day.   Yet little did Cleopatra know that it is exactly Asire's intelligence that she would need soon enough, because she had not heard the last of the Persian.</div>
