	<td class="alt1">
	
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>Befallen upon all of Persia was a great sullenness that was particularly dreadful in the palace that resides Xerxes.  The king had been humiliated.  Never in all three centuries of Persian empire’s history had such a defeat met Persian army as the one that was inflicted in the recent disastrous campaign against Egypt.  However, the king had more to worry about than the loss of his pride.  <br />
<br />
The Persian empire was built on a system based on confederation.  In the past whenever a region was conquered, that region submitted to Persian rule.  Yet, it was not completely integrated into Persian empire as a province that would be ruled directly by Persia’s imperial court.  Rather, the region would retain considerable autonomy.  So great, in fact, was the autonomy that many kings of the defeated kingdoms were allowed to continue to govern as long as they willingly surrender, swear loyalty and pay tributes and taxes to Persia.  As long as Persia’s military was perceived as unquestionably the most powerful, the allegiance of the members of Persia’s confederate empire would be ensured.  <br />
<br />
However, Xerxes feared that continued allegiance would not be the case soon, now that Persia was defeated by Egypt.  The defeat would certain hurt the reputation of Persia’s military might.  More importantly however, Persia’s military had truly been weakened, two third of her army had been lost in Egypt.  Something has to be done, and be done fast before Persia’s confederate empire disintegrate as members turn against Persia.  But what should be done?  <br />
<br />
Xerxes walked around his room all day long, skipping lunch and dinner.  By the next dawn however, an idea had come to Xerxes’ mind.  Happiness and excitement quickly took over the gloom that had only several hours ago made Xerxes such a wretched man.  He quickly dispatched his servants to gather his advisors for a meeting in which Xerxes would explain his idea, one that would conquer India first and then quell the threat of Persian empire's disintegration.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
