					Posts: 117
				</div>
				
				<div>   </div>
			</div>					
		
	</td>
	<td class="alt1">
	
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>In the summer of 3591 BC, a Persian army of ten thousands marched eastward for India's Gulpta empire.  The reason for this military manuver was that India was on the verge of a civil war as three Indian princes fought each other for Gultpa's throne.  King Xerxes of Persia knew that to attack all of India now would risk uniting the three princes and all of India; but if he were to attack India in the name of supporting one of the three competing princes to the throne to create stability in India, then King Xerxes would have the moral high ground as well as further accelerating civil war in India.  <br />
 <br />
Like a prophet, events rolled out as King Xerxes had planned. More importantly, King Xerxes selected Vijaya as the heir to India's throne.  The choice was not random for Vijaya was the least competent of the three princes, making him easier to control by Persia.  <br />
 <br />
As soon as news of Persia's support for Vijaya reached India, the two other Indian princes fled the Gulpta capital with their consituents, and build a separate kingdom of their own in those region of Gulpta empire where the princes enjoyed the greatest support, effectively dividing Gulpta into three small states, with Vijaya's located right next to Persian boarder.  <br />
 <br />
Mayamur India, ruled by Mayamur, Vijaya's second brother, was sandwiched between Vijaya India and Rajhappura India, the latter being ruled by Rajhappura, Vijaya's third brother.  Therefore Mayamur India was from the start located at a unfavorable situation, and risk attack from both sides.<br />
 <br />
Moreover, Mayamur India is a region dominated by hills and mountains with very little arable land for farming.  In time such as this when it is isolated from the rest of the India, Mayamur India would have to become completely self sufficient in provision of food, a self sufficiency that is very susceptible to disruption given the small amount of available farm land.  <br />
 <br />
King Xerxes knows this and took advantage of these facts.  For the next three years, King Xerxes would station his army of ten thousand in the boarder shared by Vijiaya India and Mayamur India, leaving another ten thousand back in Persia.  Every year when it comes close to harvesting season, King Xerxes would order his army as well as that of Vijaya India's to mobilize for invasion of Mayamur India.  King Xerxes would also spread rumor that he would dispatch his other half of Persian army stationed backin in Persia to join the invasion.  Moreover, he would spread rumor that Rajhapurra is planning an attack at around the same time.  <br />
 <br />
The reason for doing all these is to achieve to purposes.  First, by mobilizing for invasion during harvesting season, and spreading rumor that those segment of Persian army stationed in Persia would join the invasion, it created an illusion that Mayamur is going to be fighting a huge combined invasion force from both Persia and Vijaya India.  This illusion would force Mayamur to mobilize all of his country's population for war, including those farmers.  As a result of this mobilization effort, farm work would be neglected, effectively decreasing the supply of food in a country that is already volunerable to food supply disruption.  Yet after the farm duties have been sufficiently neglected to ensure a bad harvest for the year for Mayamur India, King Xerxes would always suddenly withdraw his decision to attack.  In addition, when rumors reached Persia's confederate empire that the remaining ten thousand Persian army in Persia would join King Xerxes invasion of Mayamur India, King Xerxes' spies planted throughout Persia's member states would carefully observe these states' rulers' reactions.  It is from these observations that King Xerxes would accurately determine who in Persia is prone to act of treachery.  <br />
<br />
Second, by spreading rumor that Rajhappura India is also planning an attack at around the same time, it would divide Mayamur army into two, one defending the east, the other defending the west.  <br />
 <br />
King Xerxes plan was carried out to perfection, and led to a major famine in Mayamur India three years later.  Seizing this opportunity, King Xerxes quickly ordered Vijaya's army to invade Mayamur India with King Xerxes' army following closely behind.  Thus Mayamur India was quickly brought down, with however, some loss on the part of Vijaya's army, and very insignificant loss to King Xerxes' army because his army was simply following behind Vijaya's army, which meant Vijaya's army bore the brunt of the fighting. <br />
 <br />
At the same time Rajhappura India's army also carved out a sizeable territory for herself from Mayamur India, taking advantage of the latter's famine so that India is now divided into two states.  <br />
 <br />
At this very moment, when India was divided into two, King Xerxes decided that he would ready his army and march back to Persia.  Vijaya had always been uncomfortable with the presence of King Xerxes and his army in India, and rejoiced at the news of their leaving.  However, Vijaya, being an incompetent king that he is, didn't realize that King Xerxes' leaving would encourage an attack from Rajhappura India, which is exactly what happened.  <br />
 <br />
Meanwhile as soon as King Xerxes' army marched back to Persia, he surprised all of Persia by invading with lightening speed six of Persia's member states which had planned on rebelling against Persian rule for the past three years.  King Xerxes knew of their plan because of the spie network planned since three years ago when he first left for India.  The sudden invasion caught these six member states competely offguard, and their army was quickly defeated.  With this quick victory, Persia reasserted her power and prevented the disintegration of Persia's confederate empire.  <br />
 <br />
As for India, Vijaya and Rajhappurra would fight for the next six years continuously until both were significantly weakened.  The weakening of both Vijaya India and Rajhappura India made King Xerxes' invasion of all India a very quick and easy task.  By 3582 BC, Persia had conquered all of India.  With this newly found confidence, King Xerxes would turn again to Egypt, where he would avenge his humiliating defeat a decade ago.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
