	<td class="alt1">
	
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>King Xerxes’ Indian campaign was a success.  However, having spend several years in this venture, Persian empire’s resources had been significantly drained.  If King Xerxes were to invade Egypt, he would have to do with not very much.  In fact, a Persian army of thirty thousands is all he had to conquer Egypt.  This is half of what he had in his previous Egyptian campaign.  <br />
<br />
Nevertheless, King Xerxes was confident.  He had learned from his two previous campaign that a true master of war does not rely on number and sheer size, but on strategy, and cunningness, which Egypt does not have after the death of General Asire.  <br />
<br />
--------------------------------------------<br />
<br />
Cleopatra walked along the long hallway that led to her chamber.  Something was bothering her, yet she was not sure what it is.  News of Persian navy crossing the Great Serian Lake that separates Egypt and Persia had been communicated to her and all of her royal advisors this morning during the meeting.  Plans had been formulated to counter the impending Persian threat.   The plan was simple.  It was decided that the Persians should be allowed to land on the Egyptian coast, where all of Egypt’s army would destroy the Persians before they have the time to organize after their disembarking.  In fact, at this very moment, messengers were dispatched throughout Egypt to re-deploy Egyptian troops to the bank of Great Serian Lake.  <br />
<br />
Cleopatra believes in her intuition, which is telling her that this military plan is too simplistic.  But she does not wish to be troubled by this any further, so she dismissed it right away.  Soon enough, Cleopatra would regret her decision.  <br />
<br />
--------------------------------------------------<br />
<br />
King Xerxes stood on the top deck of his warship.  From there, he has a very clear view of whatever that lay at a distance.  What King Xerxes see is land.  This is Egypt’s land, which he would conquer very soon, and with much ease.  <br />
<br />
Why would he conquer with much ease?  Because King Xerxes had fooled the Egyptian government.  King Xerxes had send for a fleet of Persian battleship to cross the Great Serian Lake to create the illusion that the Persians will invade from there.  At the same time, the real invading Persian army is being transported to the eastern tip of the Egyptian empire by another route, one that the Egyptian had never expected.  <br />
<br />
-----------------------------------------------------<br />
<br />
Cleopatra read the report.  Her face was pale white.  The Persian army had landed on the eastern tip of the Egyptian empire.  And since all of the Egyptian army was stationed along the coast of Great Serian Lake, the Persian army faced no resistance at all, and had conquered one third of Egypt by now.  <br />
<br />
Just a few hours ago, Cleopatra had ordered that the Egyptian army be completely be deployed eastward as soon as possible to throw the Persian out of Egypt.  She knows what had been bothering her now.  Her intuition had been trying to tell her that King Xerxes had been playing a big trick on her.  Yet, much to her regret, she didn’t listen to her intuition.  And now she’s playing the price for it.  <br />
<br />
------------------------------------------------------------<br />
<br />
The Persian army marched toward Thebes, the seat of Egyptian capital.  King Xerxes was confident that the Egyptian army that was coming to intercept him would be quickly destroyed.  King Xexers expected that Cleopatra would deploy the bulk of the Egyptian army to the Great Serian Lake.  And now, the Egyptian army would have to run all the way eastward to confront his Persian army.  By the time the Egyptian army does meet up with his Persian army, the former would be too tired to fight.  And King Xerxes is not planning to give the Egyptian any rest neither.  He would do unto the Egyptian what the Egyptians does onto him ten years ago.  He would make exhaust the Egyptian army even further by harassing them at night so that the already tired Egyptian army would not be able to rest.  And when morale is sufficiently low, the Egyptians could easily be destroyed.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
