	<td class="alt1">
	
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>King Xerxes sat at the throne back in the Persian capital, his countenance betraying his profound satisfaction despite his effort at trying to hide it.  He does not want his pride of the successful conquest of Egypt revealed because he wanted to be seen as a noble and benevolent king.  <br />
<br />
Kneeling before him is Queen Cleopatra, who has submitted to Persian rule in exchange for some form of Egyptian autonomy.  King Xerxes knew of Egyptian's love for Queen Cleopatra and did not wish to alienate his new subjects by executing the queen, so he agreed to Egyptian autonomy.  In fact, since Persian empire is really a confederate empire, the Egyptian autonomy is nothing new anyways.  <br />
<br />
King Xerxes had completed the conquest of all Middle East after almost fifteen years.  For the next eighty years, Middle East would be united under one central authority.  Prosperity and peace would reign, and arts, literatures, sciences and cultures would flourish, ushering the first of many Golden Age in Middle Eastern history.</div>
